      Uninsured deposits
   =20
 =20

Ahahaha  in possibly related news:

The largest US banks have been rushing to restate their financials in order=
 to minimise how much they may have to pay to cover the cost of the failure=
s this year of Silicon Valley Bank and Signature Bank. ...
The FDIC regularly assesses banks with a fee for providing deposit insuranc=
e, but in May, it proposed a special assessment for this year=E2=80=99s maj=
or failures.
The fees were computed based on banks=E2=80=99 uninsured deposits, as $15.8=
bn of the $18.5bn cost of the SVB and Signature bailouts were due to the co=
verage of accounts larger than the FDIC=E2=80=99s normal $250,000 insured l=
imit. Most of those accounts were with large banks.
The corporation wanted to apply the assessment based on the value of the ba=
nks=E2=80=99 uninsured deposits at the end of 2022. ...
Analysts at S&P Global noted in a report that an unusually high number of b=
anks in the past six months had restated their uninsured deposits as of the=
 end of last year. S&P said 55 banks this year had restated their fourth-qu=
arter figure, compared with just 14 in the same quarter the prior year. S&P=
 said the majority of the restatements resulted in lower uninsured deposits=
.
Bank of America had the largest restatement, cutting its uninsured deposits=
 by $125bn, or nearly 14 per cent, according to the report. Based on its lo=
wer uninsured deposits, S&P said BofA=E2=80=99s special assessment would dr=
op to $1.95bn, down from $2.26bn. ...
BofA declined to comment. It had told S&P it had improperly characterised s=
ome of the bank=E2=80=99s own cash as customer deposits, resulting in the r=
estatement. A source close to BofA told the Financial Times that the restat=
ement was made in early May, days before the FDIC released the framework fo=
r its proposed assessment.

The FDIC is   not pleased; it published a Financial Institution Letter obje=
cting to some of the adjustments the banks have made:
The FDIC observed that some insured depository institutions (IDIs) are not =
reporting estimated uninsured deposits in accordance with the instructions =
to the Consolidated Reports of Condition and Income (Call Report). For exam=
ple, some institutions incorrectly reduced the amount reported to the exten=
t that the uninsured deposits are collateralized by pledged assets; this is=
 incorrect because in and of itself, the existence of collateral has no bea=
ring on the portion of a deposit that is covered by federal deposit insuran=
ce. Additionally, some institutions incorrectly reduced the amount reported=
 on Schedule RC-O by excluding intercompany deposit balances of subsidiarie=
s.
You might naively think that if you asked one of the largest banks in the U=
S =E2=80=9Chow much money do you have from depositors with more than $250,0=
00 at your bank,=E2=80=9D it could spend, you know, a few hours looking at =
the data and get back to you with an answer that was accurate to within 10%=
. But you=E2=80=99d be wrong!

 =20
   =20
      The APE arb
   =20
 =20

AMC Entertainment Holdings has two types of stock: common shares (ticker AM=
C) and AMC Preferred Equity Units (ticker APE). These are supposed to be ec=
onomically equivalent, but they trade at very different prices. The common =
stock closed at $5.85 yesterday; the APEs closed at $1.80. AMC has announce=
d plans to convert the APEs into common stock; the formula is somewhat comp=
licated but roughly speaking each APE would turn into 0.88 common shares.
  [1]
=C2=A0If the common stock is really worth $5.85, then an APE should be wort=
h about $5.16. If the APEs are really worth $1.80, then each common share s=
hould be worth about $2.04. Or pick some numbers in the middle. The point i=
s, the $5.85/$1.80 disparity seems odd.
Of course the disparity exists because, as we have discussed a lot,   inclu=
ding yesterday, AMC common shareholders sued to stop AMC from converting th=
e APEs into common, and a court has held up the proposed conversion. The sh=
areholder plaintiffs and AMC have reached a settlement, but the court has n=
ot approved the settlement yet; on Friday, the judge, Delaware Vice Chancel=
lor Morgan Zurn, rejected the settlement because it gave AMC too broad a re=
lease from legal liability. (This is what we discussed yesterday.) AMC and =
the plaintiffs pretty much immediately sent back a revised settlement, cros=
sing out the broad release and thus answering the judge=E2=80=99s objection=
s.
Now what? Well, the good news (for AMC, and for the APEs) is that the judge=
   will consider the revised settlement quickly:

AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. and shareholders leading litigation against=
 the theater chain can immediately renew their efforts to get court approva=
l for a settlement that would let the company convert its APE units into co=
mmon stock, a judge said Monday.
Vice Chancellor Morgan T. Zurn, who stunned analysts by rejecting the origi=
nal agreement July 21, said the deal approval process can resume without a =
delay that would let AMC=E2=80=99s passionate retail investors file new obj=
ections. =E2=80=9CThe narrowed release does not adversely affect the putati=
ve class,=E2=80=9D she said in a letter to both sides of the court fight, s=
uggesting the new deal could be approved in August. ...
Zurn, writing Monday for Delaware=E2=80=99s Chancery Court, said she was se=
nsitive to AMC=E2=80=99s recapitalization needs, which the company has call=
ed urgent as recently as Sunday, when CEO Adam Aron published an open lette=
r stressing the risk of =E2=80=9Cfinancial collapse.=E2=80=9D AMC previousl=
y requested a ruling =E2=80=9Cbefore the capital markets go quiet in August=
,=E2=80=9D the judge noted.

The bad news is that it is still not quite certain that she will approve th=
e revised settlement, or when. It answers the objections that she raised on=
 Friday, but her opinion on Friday did not say =E2=80=9Cthis settlement is =
fine except for this one thing=E2=80=9D; it just raised the one thing.=C2=
=A0I=C2=A0think the settlement is fine, and the special master appointed by=
 Vice Chancellor Zurn to review the settlement found it was fine, but it=E2=
=80=99s up to her, and she hasn=E2=80=99t ruled yet one way or the other. (=
The  Chancery Daily newsletter, for one, is skeptical that Vice Chancellor =
Zurn has an opinion ready approving the settlement: =E2=80=9CIf she had the=
 whole thing done, why would she have held it back?=E2=80=9D)
AMC=E2=80=99s common shares and its APEs have always been meant to be one-f=
or-one (or, now, one-for-0.88) substitutes for each other, always meant to =
merge into each other eventually. And so there is an arbitrage: Hedge funds=
 can buy APEs (for $1.80 or whatever), sell 0.88 common shares short (for $=
5.85 per share, or $5.16 per 0.88 shares), and pocket the roughly $3.36 pro=
fit when the APEs convert.
  [2]

And they have done that =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a long time =E2=80=94=C2=A0and i=
t has been   an absolute nightmare for them:

Investors betting on the conversion were shorting shares of the common stoc=
k and snapping up AMC=E2=80=99s preferred units on the expectation that the=
 price gap between the pair would vanish as the deal goes through, allowing=
 them to capture the spread.
While it was supposed to be a straightforward bet =E2=80=94 with traders ex=
pecting to reap a windfall in a short period of time =E2=80=94 it hasn=E2=
=80=99t played out that way.
The expensive cost to short the meme stock=E2=80=99s common shares, paired =
with the volatility given its retail-trader following, also kept the spread=
 wider than $2 since the APEs were distributed last year.

The problem is that, to short AMC common shares, you have to borrow them, a=
nd that=E2=80=99s expensive, with short sellers paying something north of 8=
00% annualized to borrow the common, according to S3 Research data. Call th=
at rate 20% per month, or about $1 per month per common share, which eats p=
retty rapidly into your $3.36 profit. The conversion was   supposed to happ=
en in March; now the best case is August. It has been an unpleasant trade.
Incidentally, this is=C2=A0why=C2=A0the gap exists between the common stock=
 and APE prices. Some of it is due to uncertainty =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe Vice=
 Chancellor Zurn will reject the settlement and=C2=A0never=C2=A0allow the A=
PEs to convert =E2=80=94=C2=A0but most of it is probably due to limits to a=
rbitrage. If you notice the gap and say =E2=80=9Chey, these APEs are tradin=
g at a huge discount to the common, I bet that gap will close,=E2=80=9D tha=
t=E2=80=99s fine, but you=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0actually make that bet ec=
onomically.
  [3]
 Arbitrageurs can=E2=80=99t really close the gap between the share classes:=
 They tried, and got burned.
It=E2=80=99s still a bit of a weird gap. If you are an AMC shareholder, you=
 could always=C2=A0sell your AMC shares and buy APEs:=C2=A0If you are not=
=C2=A0short=C2=A0selling, you don=E2=80=99t need to borrow the stock, so yo=
u can easily swap into the APEs. Sell one AMC share for $5.85 and buy three=
 APEs, with some change left over; the APEs will eventually convert back in=
to common shares (probably! not certainly! not legal or investing advice!) =
and you=E2=80=99ll get free extra shares. But:
=09A lot of AMC shareholders are meme-stock believers who do not=C2=A0want=
=C2=A0the APEs=C2=A0to convert into common stock, are trying to prevent it,=
 don=E2=80=99t believe it will happen, and therefore have no reason to bet =
on the gap closing.=09If you are an=C2=A0institutional=C2=A0AMC shareholder=
, sure you can sell your common shares and buy many more APEs. But if you i=
nstead hold the common shares,=C2=A0you can make a lot of money lending the=
m out:=C2=A0Those super-expensive stock-borrow costs paid by short sellers =
end up getting paid (largely) to the share owners who lend out their common=
 shares. The common stock has a higher price than=C2=A0the APEs in part bec=
ause it is=C2=A0worth more:=C2=A0The common stock comes with share-lending =
cash flows, while the APEs do not.


 =20
   =20
      iRobot
   =20
 =20

We   talked a couple of weeks ago about the mechanics of a public-company m=
erger. Specifically, I pointed out that public-company acquisitions don=E2=
=80=99t generally have price adjustments for changes in=C2=A0the target=E2=
=80=99s financial situation between signing and closing. If you sign an agr=
eement in April=C2=A0to buy a public company for $54.20 per share, expectin=
g it to have $1 billion in cash at closing, and then when the deal closes i=
n October it only has $900 million in cash, you don=E2=80=99t get to knock =
a dollar or two off the purchase price. The company is less valuable at clo=
sing than you thought it would be, but there=E2=80=99s not a lot you can do=
 about it.=C2=A0This is partly because, when you sign an agreement to buy a=
 public company, the company needs to have a shareholder vote to approve th=
e deal, and the shareholders need to know what they are voting on. If the p=
rice can change at the last minute, it=E2=80=99s hard to do the vote.
That said, there are limits: If the company=E2=80=99s cash goes from $1 bil=
lion to $0, perhaps there has been a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=
=9D that gives you the right to get out of the deal. Or if the company deci=
des to pay its chief executive officer a $1 billion special bonus for being=
 such a great CEO, that might not be =E2=80=9Cin the ordinary course of bus=
iness,=E2=80=9D which would also give you a right to get out of the deal.=
=C2=A0The merger agreement will say things like =E2=80=9Cthe company can=E2=
=80=99t pay bonuses outside of the ordinary course of business without the =
buyer=E2=80=99s permission,=E2=80=9D and so if the company wants to pay a b=
ig bonus it will have to ask you first, and you can say no and preserve the=
 cash for yourself.
Similarly, if you expect the company to have some money at closing, but it =
runs through its money too fast and has to=C2=A0borrow=C2=A0more money to s=
tay afloat, that will reduce the value of the company to you, and you=C2=A0=
probably=C2=A0do=C2=A0get to do something about it. The  merger agreement w=
ill say=C2=A0something like =E2=80=9Cthe Company will not =E2=80=A6=C2=A0cr=
eate, incur, assume, guarantee, endorse, suffer to exist or otherwise be li=
able with respect to any indebtedness for borrowed money.=E2=80=9D Between =
signing of the merger agreement and closing, the target company can=E2=80=
=99t go around borrowing money without your permission. That would change t=
he deal.
And the way that works in practice is that, if the company=C2=A0does=C2=A0n=
eed to borrow money, it will come to you for permission, and you will say s=
omething like =E2=80=9Cwell I see that you need the money, but this makes y=
our company worth less than I thought it would be, so I want a price reduct=
ion.=E2=80=9D And then you will just   negotiate a price reduction in excha=
nge for your permission:

IRobot Corp. tumbled after Amazon.com Inc. lowered the price it=E2=80=99s p=
aying for the Roomba maker to $51.75 per share from $61 per share.
IRobot has entered into a $200 million financing facility to fund its ongoi=
ng operations, the companies said in a statement. That prompted Amazon to c=
hange the price to offset the planned increase in iRobot=E2=80=99s net debt=
.
IRobot shares fell about 8.9% to $42.73 as markets opened in New York, whil=
e Amazon was largely unchanged.

Note that that price is well below $51.75, because =E2=80=9Csince Amazon an=
nounced the transaction last August, the Federal Trade Commission and Europ=
ean regulators have been probing the deal.=E2=80=9D Here are iRobot=E2=80=
=99s  filing announcing the amendment, and the press release saying that =
=E2=80=9Cthe change in price per share is expected to be largely offset by =
the planned increase in iRobot=E2=80=99s net debt under the new financing f=
acility.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Largely=C2=A0offset: The company has about 27 millio=
n shares outstanding, so the $9.25 per share price reduction is worth about=
 $250 million, which is more than $200 million. But if the company you are =
buying comes to you and says =E2=80=9Chey uh bad news we=E2=80=99re out of =
cash and need to borrow more, that=E2=80=99s okay right,=E2=80=9D you are g=
oing to exact a price for saying yes.

 =20
   =20
      Multistrategy funds
   =20
 =20

Here are two ways to run a hedge fund:
=09Be a charismatic genius investor. Pick some companies that you think are=
 good, buy their stocks, hold them for a fairly long term, maybe do a bit o=
f activism to improve their performance. Pick some companies that you think=
 are bad, short their stocks, maybe do a bit of short activism to get every=
one to see their flaws. Have a concentrated portfolio of a dozen or so name=
s, bet big with conviction, hope you=E2=80=99re right.=09Hire like 30 geniu=
s investors and scientifically analyze their investing styles and track rec=
ords to break down exactly how they add value. Pay them only to do that: He=
dge out all of their exposure to the broad stock market, and to factors lik=
e value and momentum, so that they are not getting paid just for owning sto=
cks in a bull market (or owning tech stocks in a tech bubble), but only for=
 picking exactly which stocks will outperform which other stocks. Because e=
verything is hedged, they won=E2=80=99t benefit from broad market movements=
, and they probably won=E2=80=99t make all that=C2=A0much=C2=A0of a return.=
 But because everything is hedged, you can=C2=A0leverage=C2=A0it a lot: You=
 can take $1 of investor capital, buy $10 of good stocks, short $10 of bad =
stocks, and if the good stocks are up 10% and the bad ones are up 8% then y=
ou have a 20% return on capital.

Crudely speaking, the first approach was the popular image of hedge-fund ma=
nagement for much of its history, and the second approach =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
e =E2=80=9Cmulti-manager=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cmultistrategy=E2=80=9D fund=
=C2=A0or =E2=80=9Cpod shop=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0has become increasi=
ngly dominant in recent years. There are reasons for this. For one thing, t=
he pod shops, with their scientific performance measurement, can more convi=
ncingly promise their clients that they are delivering uncorrelated returns=
, that they are good rather than just lucky. Also, clients like that they a=
re more institutional and less reliant on one charismatic genius, which mak=
es them less susceptible to succession drama. Also, there is reason to thin=
k that the skills of (1) making investment decisions, (2) charming clients =
and (3) running the operations of a company are all pretty separate, and th=
e multi-manager funds can hire people who are good at making investment dec=
isions, let them do that, and have someone else handle the rest of it.
At FT Alphaville, Rupak Ghose points out another important aspect of pod sh=
ops, which is that they are structurally much better clients for banks:

Many of the most successful equity long/short managers of recent decades =
=E2=80=94 such as Viking, Lone Pine, TCI, Lansdowne, and Egerton =E2=80=94 =
had very different investment styles from the dominant multi-strategy shops=
. The former had more concentrated investment portfolios and less churn, an=
d were closer to long-only growth funds than multi-strategy =E2=80=9Cpods=
=E2=80=9D. (Remember, capital is often pulled away from a =E2=80=9Cpod=E2=
=80=9D when it is down 5 per cent, and the =E2=80=9Cpod=E2=80=9D closed alt=
ogether if it is down 10 per cent.)
Commissions to sellside banks and data vendors are consequently much larger=
 for pod shops. Similarly, equity long/short funds tend to deploy leverage =
that is order of magnitudes lower than multi-strategy and systematic firms =
that are in vogue today, meaning the industry=E2=80=99s AUM packs a greater=
 punch.

Being really scientific about performance measurement tends to mean trading=
 a lot and borrowing a lot of money, both of which make you a good client o=
f banks. Buying a dozen stocks, shorting four more, and holding them for ye=
ars makes you less exciting for the banks.=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      Too much trading
   =20
 =20

If you are a retail stock investor, which is better:
=09Sometimes trading stocks for a bit, on your lunch break at work, or=09Tr=
ading stocks all night, sometimes looking up from your brokerage website to=
 see the sun rising?

I mean! Intuitively, if you like trading stocks, trading stocks all night l=
ong might be more=C2=A0fun=C2=A0than having to fit it into the workday. But=
 if you are having fun trading stocks all night long, you are probably maki=
ng less money? I would guess?
That is just a guess. Here=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CTrading Hours and Retail Inve=
stment Performance=E2=80=9D by=C2=A0Ed deHaan and Andrew Glover:
This paper examines the effects of stock market access, and in particular t=
rading hours, on retail investment performance. We find that plausibly exog=
enous increases in trading hours are associated with meaningful declines in=
 retail investors=E2=80=99 capital gains, as reported on tax returns for th=
e U.S. population. Our results indicate that increasing trading hours exace=
rbates retail investors=E2=80=99 tendencies to trade =E2=80=9Ctoo much,=E2=
=80=9D leading to declines in portfolio performance. Our findings inform di=
scussions among academics, practitioners, and regulators about the potentia=
l detrimental effects of decreasing barriers to entry for retail investors =
in trading markets.
=E2=80=9CWe find that a one-hour decrease in waking trading hours is associ=
ated with a 3.9 percentage point increase in investment performance,=E2=80=
=9D they write, though to be fair they are talking about trading during =E2=
=80=9Cnormal productive waking hours=E2=80=9D: They use time-zone discontin=
uities to argue that investors who are at work during more of the market=E2=
=80=99s hours have more trading time, and those investors do worse than inv=
estors (say in California) who get to their desks=C2=A0after the market has=
 already been going for a while.
I don=E2=80=99t know if that answers my question? Another way to put that i=
s that investors who have more time to trade=C2=A0outside=C2=A0of normal wo=
rking hours =E2=80=94=C2=A0who have to wake up early to feed their obsessio=
n =E2=80=94=C2=A0do=C2=A0better=C2=A0than the ones who can only trade durin=
g working hours. But they do write:
The generalizability of our empirical findings warrants discussion. Our set=
ting limits access in the first hour(s) of regular trading, when volume, vo=
latility, spreads, and adverse selection are especially high. Adverse selec=
tion and spreads are often even higher outside of regular hours (Barclay & =
Hendershott 2004), and recent research finds that news-driven volatility is=
 now also higher out-of-hours than during the day (Boudoukh et al. 2019).=
=C2=A0Thus, our findings from the first hour(s) of regular trading should b=
e informative about the likely effects of increasing retail investors=E2=80=
=99 out-of-hours trading access.=C2=A0
Yeah no the market is not going to be=C2=A0efficient=C2=A0if you are tradin=
g at midnight, but efficient is maybe not what you want.

