<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC Entertainment Holdings has two types of st=
ock: common shares (ticker AMC) and AMC Preferred Equity Units (ticker APE)=
. These are supposed to be economically equivalent, but they trade at very =
different prices. The common stock closed at $5.85 yesterday; the APEs clos=
ed at $1.80. AMC has announced plans to convert the APEs into common stock;=
 the formula is somewhat complicated but roughly speaking each APE would tu=
rn into 0.88 common shares.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If the common stock is really worth $5.85, then an APE should be =
worth about $5.16. If the APEs are really worth $1.80, then each common sha=
re should be worth about $2.04. Or pick some numbers in the middle. The poi=
nt is, the $5.85/$1.80 disparity seems odd.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course the disparity exists because, as we =
have discussed a lot, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/32188809.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjMtMDctMjQvdGhlLWFwZXMtY2FuLWJlLXNhdmVkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MjUyM19NT05FWV=
NUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzM=
DcyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8dbfa829" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  including yesterday</a>, AMC common shareholders sued to stop AMC f=
rom converting the APEs into common, and a court has held up the proposed c=
onversion. The shareholder plaintiffs and AMC have reached a settlement, bu=
t the court has not approved the settlement yet; on Friday, the judge, Dela=
ware Vice Chancellor Morgan Zurn, rejected the settlement because it gave A=
MC too broad a release from legal liability. (This is what we discussed yes=
terday.) AMC and the plaintiffs pretty much immediately sent back a revised=
 settlement, crossing out the broad release and thus answering the judge=E2=
=80=99s objections.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now what? Well, the good news (for AMC, and fo=
r the APEs) is that the judge <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/32188809.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vZW52aXJ=
vbm1lbnQtYW5kLWVuZXJneS9hbWNzLXJldmlzZWQtYXBlLWRlYWwtaGVhZHMtYmFjay10by1qdW=
RnZS1vbi1leHBlZGl0ZWQtdGltZWxpbmU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcabe0c01" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">  will consider the revised settlement quickly</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. and shareholde=
rs leading litigation against the theater chain can immediately renew their=
 efforts to get court approval for a settlement that would let the company =
convert its APE units into common stock, a judge said Monday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Vice Chancellor Morgan T. Zurn, who stunned an=
alysts by rejecting the original agreement July 21, said the deal approval =
process can resume without a delay that would let AMC=E2=80=99s passionate =
retail investors file new objections. =E2=80=9CThe narrowed release does no=
t adversely affect the putative class,=E2=80=9D she said in a letter to bot=
h sides of the court fight, suggesting the new deal could be approved in Au=
gust. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Zurn, writing Monday for Delaware=E2=80=99s Ch=
ancery Court, said she was sensitive to AMC=E2=80=99s recapitalization need=
s, which the company has called urgent as recently as Sunday, when CEO Adam=
 Aron published an open letter stressing the risk of =E2=80=9Cfinancial col=
lapse.=E2=80=9D AMC previously requested a ruling =E2=80=9Cbefore the capit=
al markets go quiet in August,=E2=80=9D the judge noted.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bad news is that it is still not quite cer=
tain that she will approve the revised settlement, or when. It answers the =
objections that she raised on Friday, but her opinion on Friday did not say=
 =E2=80=9Cthis settlement is fine except for this one thing=E2=80=9D; it ju=
st raised the one thing.=C2=A0<em>I=C2=A0</em>think the settlement is fine,=
 and the special master appointed by Vice Chancellor Zurn to review the set=
tlement <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32188809.2=
58411/aHR0cHM6Ly9zMjUucTRjZG4uY29tLzQ3MjY0MzYwOC9maWxlcy9kb2NfZG93bmxvYWRzL=
3NoYXJlaG9sZGVyLW1lZXRpbmcvMjAyMy8wNi9SZXBvcnQtYW5kLVJlY29tbWVuZGF0aW9uLW9m=
LVNwZWNpYWwtTWFzdGVyLVJlZ2FyZGluZy1PYmplY3Rpb25zLXRvLVByb3Bvc2VkLVNldHRsZW1=
lbnQtd2l0aC1FeGhpYml0cy1hbmQtQXBwZW5kaWNlcy5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa=
bbdf93e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">found it was fine</a>, but it=E2=80=99s up to her, and she=
 hasn=E2=80=99t ruled yet one way or the other. (The <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32188809.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly90aGVjaGFuY2Vy=
eWRhaWx5LnN1YnN0YWNrLmNvbS9wL2FtYy1pZi1vbmUtbW9yZS1icm8tc2F5cy10aGlzLWlt/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe2d9cf0f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Chancery Daily newsletter</a>, fo=
r one, is skeptical that Vice Chancellor Zurn has an opinion ready approvin=
g the settlement: =E2=80=9CIf she had the whole thing done, why would she h=
ave held it back?=E2=80=9D)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC=E2=80=99s common shares and its APEs have =
always been meant to be one-for-one (or, now, one-for-0.88) substitutes for=
 each other, always meant to merge into each other eventually. And so there=
 is an arbitrage: Hedge funds can buy APEs (for $1.80 or whatever), sell 0.=
88 common shares short (for $5.85 per share, or $5.16 per 0.88 shares), and=
 pocket the roughly $3.36 profit when the APEs convert.<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And they have done that =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a l=
ong time =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it has been <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/32188809.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMjQvYW1jLWFwZS1hcmItYmxvd24tb3V0LWZyaWRheS1nZXRz=
LWxpZmVsaW5lLWZyb20tbmV3LWZpbGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA3MjUmdXRtX2=
NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1c36878f" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  an a=
bsolute nightmare for them</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors betting on the conversion were short=
ing shares of the common stock and snapping up AMC=E2=80=99s preferred unit=
s on the expectation that the price gap between the pair would vanish as th=
e deal goes through, allowing them to capture the spread.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While it was supposed to be a straightforward =
bet =E2=80=94 with traders expecting to reap a windfall in a short period o=
f time =E2=80=94 it hasn=E2=80=99t played out that way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The expensive cost to short the meme stock=E2=
=80=99s common shares, paired with the volatility given its retail-trader f=
ollowing, also kept the spread wider than $2 since the APEs were distribute=
d last year.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that, to short AMC common share=
s, you have to borrow them, and that=E2=80=99s expensive, with short seller=
s paying something north of 800% annualized to borrow the common, according=
 to S3 Research data. Call that rate 20% per month, or about $1 per month p=
er common share, which eats pretty rapidly into your $3.36 profit. The conv=
ersion was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3218880=
9.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMD=
ItMjgvYW1jLXMtYXBlcy1oYXZlLXRvLXdhaXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDcyNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmd=
XRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNzI1JnV0=
bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc0ccde4a" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  s=
upposed to happen in March</a>; now the best case is August. It has been an=
 unpleasant trade.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally, this is=C2=A0<em>why=C2=A0</em>t=
he gap exists between the common stock and APE prices. Some of it is due to=
 uncertainty =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe Vice Chancellor Zurn will reject the sett=
lement and=C2=A0<em>never=C2=A0</em>allow the APEs to convert =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but most of it is probably due to limits to arbitrage. If you notice the=
 gap and say =E2=80=9Chey, these APEs are trading at a huge discount to the=
 common, I bet that gap will close,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s fine, but you=
=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>actually make that bet economically.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> Arbitrageurs can=E2=80=99t really close the gap between the share clas=
ses: They tried, and got burned.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s still a bit of a weird gap. If yo=
u are an AMC shareholder, you could always=C2=A0<em>sell your AMC shares an=
d buy APEs:=C2=A0</em>If you are not=C2=A0<em>short=C2=A0</em>selling, you =
don=E2=80=99t need to borrow the stock, so you can easily swap into the APE=
s. Sell one AMC share for $5.85 and buy three APEs, with some change left o=
ver; the APEs will eventually convert back into common shares (probably! no=
t certainly! not legal or investing advice!) and you=E2=80=99ll get free ex=
tra shares. But:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A lot of AMC shareholders are meme-st=
ock believers who do not=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>the APEs=C2=A0to convert i=
nto common stock, are trying to prevent it, don=E2=80=99t believe it will h=
appen, and therefore have no reason to bet on the gap closing.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are an=C2=A0<em>institutional=C2=A0</em=
>AMC shareholder, sure you can sell your common shares and buy many more AP=
Es. But if you instead hold the common shares,=C2=A0<em>you can make a lot =
of money lending them out:=C2=A0</em>Those super-expensive stock-borrow cos=
ts paid by short sellers end up getting paid (largely) to the share owners =
who lend out their common shares. The common stock has a higher price than=
=C2=A0the APEs in part because it is=C2=A0<em>worth more:=C2=A0</em>The com=
mon stock comes with share-lending cash flows, while the APEs do not.</li>
</ol>
