itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked a coup=
le of weeks ago</a> about the mechanics of a public-company merger. Specifi=
cally, I pointed out that public-company acquisitions don=E2=80=99t general=
ly have price adjustments for changes in=C2=A0the target=E2=80=99s financia=
l situation between signing and closing. If you sign an agreement in April=
=C2=A0to buy a public company for $54.20 per share, expecting it to have $1=
 billion in cash at closing, and then when the deal closes in October it on=
ly has $900 million in cash, you don=E2=80=99t get to knock a dollar or two=
 off the purchase price. The company is less valuable at closing than you t=
hought it would be, but there=E2=80=99s not a lot you can do about it.=C2=
=A0This is partly because, when you sign an agreement to buy a public compa=
ny, the company needs to have a shareholder vote to approve the deal, and t=
he shareholders need to know what they are voting on. If the price can chan=
ge at the last minute, it=E2=80=99s hard to do the vote.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, there are limits: If the company=E2=
=80=99s cash goes from $1 billion to $0, perhaps there has been a =E2=80=9C=
material adverse effect=E2=80=9D that gives you the right to get out of the=
 deal. Or if the company decides to pay its chief executive officer a $1 bi=
llion special bonus for being such a great CEO, that might not be =E2=80=9C=
in the ordinary course of business,=E2=80=9D which would also give you a ri=
ght to get out of the deal.=C2=A0The merger agreement will say things like =
=E2=80=9Cthe company can=E2=80=99t pay bonuses outside of the ordinary cour=
se of business without the buyer=E2=80=99s permission,=E2=80=9D and so if t=
he company wants to pay a big bonus it will have to ask you first, and you =
can say no and preserve the cash for yourself.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, if you expect the company to have s=
ome money at closing, but it runs through its money too fast and has to=C2=
=A0<em>borrow=C2=A0</em>more money to stay afloat, that will reduce the val=
ue of the company to you, and you=C2=A0probably=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>get t=
o do something about it. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/32188809.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9k=
YXRhLzExNTkxNjcvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMjQwMDYyL2QyOTA5MDBkZGVmbTE0YS5odG0jdG9jMjk=
