<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a retail stock investor, which is b=
etter:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sometimes trading stocks for a bit, o=
n your lunch break at work, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Tra=
ding stocks all night, sometimes looking up from your brokerage website to =
see the sun rising?</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean! Intuitively, if you like trading stock=
s, trading stocks all night long might be more=C2=A0<em>fun=C2=A0</em>than =
having to fit it into the workday. But if you are having fun trading stocks=
 all night long, you are probably making less money? I would guess?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is just a guess. Here=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32188809.258411/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQ0ODY3M=
jE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfc3c2aeb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Trading Hours and Retail Inve=
stment Performance</a>=E2=80=9D by=C2=A0Ed deHaan and Andrew Glover:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This paper examines the effects of=
 stock market access, and in particular trading hours, on retail investment=
 performance. We find that plausibly exogenous increases in trading hours a=
re associated with meaningful declines in retail investors=E2=80=99 capital=
 gains, as reported on tax returns for the U.S. population. Our results ind=
icate that increasing trading hours exacerbates retail investors=E2=80=99 t=
endencies to trade =E2=80=9Ctoo much,=E2=80=9D leading to declines in portf=
olio performance. Our findings inform discussions among academics, practiti=
oners, and regulators about the potential detrimental effects of decreasing=
 barriers to entry for retail investors in trading markets.</p></blockquote=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe find that a one-hour decrease in w=
aking trading hours is associated with a 3.9 percentage point increase in i=
nvestment performance,=E2=80=9D they write, though to be fair they are talk=
ing about trading during =E2=80=9Cnormal productive waking hours=E2=80=9D: =
They use time-zone discontinuities to argue that investors who are at work =
during more of the market=E2=80=99s hours have more trading time, and those=
 investors do worse than investors (say in California) who get to their des=
ks=C2=A0after the market has already been going for a while.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know if that answers my questi=
on? Another way to put that is that investors who have more time to trade=
=C2=A0<em>outside=C2=A0</em>of normal working hours =E2=80=94=C2=A0who have=
 to wake up early to feed their obsession =E2=80=94=C2=A0do=C2=A0<em>better=
=C2=A0</em>than the ones who can only trade during working hours. But they =
do write:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The generalizability of our empiri=
cal findings warrants discussion. Our setting limits access in the first ho=
ur(s) of regular trading, when volume, volatility, spreads, and adverse sel=
ection are especially high. Adverse selection and spreads are often even hi=
gher outside of regular hours (Barclay &amp; Hendershott 2004), and recent =
research finds that news-driven volatility is now also higher out-of-hours =
than during the day (Boudoukh et al. 2019).=C2=A0Thus, our findings from th=
e first hour(s) of regular trading should be informative about the likely e=
ffects of increasing retail investors=E2=80=99 out-of-hours trading access.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah no the market is not going to be=C2=A0<em=
>efficient=C2=A0</em>if you are trading at midnight, but efficient is maybe=
 not what you want.</p>
